## This template

Exercises the `sensor.w25q32` driver and the `IExternalFlash` interface.
Run once at boot, output goes over USART2 (115200 baud, interrupt mode).

### Pinout (SPI2)

| Function | Pin | Notes |
|----------|-----|-------|
| SPI2 SCK | PB13 | AF5 |
| SPI2 MISO | PB14 | AF5 |
| SPI2 MOSI | PB15 | AF5 |
| W25Q32 CS | PB12 | output, push-pull, driven low during transactions |
| USART2 TX | PA2 | AF7, log output |

SPI2 clock: 10 MHz. UART: 115200 baud.

### Connect the W25Q32

| Flash pin | STM32 pin |
|-----------|-----------|
| VCC | 3.3 V |
| GND | GND |
| CS | PB12 |
| CLK | PB13 |
| DO (MISO) | PB14 |
| DI (MOSI) | PB15 |
| WP | 3.3 V (write-protect disabled) |
| HOLD | 3.3 V (hold disabled) |

### Expected serial output

```
W25Q32 round-trip test
JEDEC ID: 0xEF4016
erase sector 0x00000000 ... ok
page program 0x00000000 ... ok
read 0x00000000 .. 0x0000003F:
  A0 A1 A2 A3 A4 A5 A6 A7 A8 A9 AA AB AC AD AE AF
  B0 B1 B2 B3 B4 B5 B6 B7 B8 B9 BA BB BC BD BE BF
  C0 C1 C2 C3 C4 C5 C6 C7 C8 C9 CA CB CC CD CE CF
  D0 D1 D2 D3 D4 D5 D6 D7 D8 D9 DA DB DC DD DE DF
VERIFY OK
```

The JEDEC ID `0xEF4016` identifies W25Q32JV (Winbond, 32 Mbit). If you see
a different ID:

| ID prefix | Manufacturer |
|-----------|--------------|
| `0xEF` | Winbond |
| `0xC8` | GigaDevice |
| `0x68` | BoyaMicro |

### How to verify

1. Open the FTDI serial port **before** resetting the MCU (macOS flushes the
   RX FIFO when the port is first opened — the test output is one-shot).
2. Reset the board.
3. Confirm `JEDEC ID: 0xEF4016` (or another valid value for your chip).
4. The 64 hex bytes match the pattern `A0..AF, B0..BF, C0..CF, D0..DF`.
5. Final line is `VERIFY OK`.

If no output:
- Check that USART2 TX (PA2) is wired to FTDI RX.
- Confirm SPI2 wiring; the simplest miswiring is MISO/MOSI swap.
- Verify VCC is 3.3 V — W25Q32 is not 5 V tolerant.

### When to extend

The driver also supports `chipErase()` (slow — seconds), `eraseSector()` at
any 4 KiB-aligned address, and `read()` of arbitrary length. Total capacity
is 4 MiB (32 Mbit, 1024 sectors × 4 KiB).
